text: You know...they can easily pull a big twist here. For all we know, it really could be Gage. Look at what they did for Infinity War, by redoing scenes and clipping them together to make it so you believe it will go one way and in reality it could go another. If it does end up with Ellie dying instead of Gage, then I would enjoy the twist. But I also hope they do turn the tables on us, making us expect that Ellie is going to die only to watch them bury Gage and bring him back. Make us expect one thing and shock us by giving us the exact opposite of what we expected. Either way, this movie looks good. And with the markings on the tree gives me a real Dark Tower vibe. Hoping they create the Stephen King Cinematic Universe or whatever.

text: For those people saying that swapping out Gage's death for Ellie's is a bad thing, remember that in the Jurassic Park book, Dr. Malcolm was supposed to die, but he survived in the movie. A movie shouldn't always have to cling to the source material. They can do their own thing. Look at Steven Spielberg's Jaws. That movie was based on a book and Spielberg himself said he took a lot of liberties with that movie, because he thought the characters were so unlikable, that he was rooting for the shark to eat all of them.

And if,¬†for some reason, they have deliberately made it look as though Ellie is the one¬†to die, and it really is Gage, those masks are ridiculous and dumb everything down to appeal to newer audiences. text: Kinda of ruined the story there with killing off Ellen Creed. I mean directors like to put their own twists and  interpretations into the scripts, i mean Lamberts movie had her own interpretations aswell. Ones Stephen King even thought were better. But Gages death is really important and I feel should've stayed. Plus kind of a spoiler showing her coming back from the Micmac. The part I do like is how the Wendigo is a big part of the remake  as it was a huge part of the book and almost entirely ignored in the 89' movie besides the mention of loons. As a purest to the original film, and I know that I wont be alone on this, it will be lacking in the Fred Gwynne department, as his portrayal of Jud made that whole movie what it was. I do wonder if Missy will commit suicide or of Jud will be married to Norma and she dies from an Heart Attack. I'm really excited to see this movie, though my expectations are going to be low going into the theater in April.

text: This is the most 'whole-film-in-a-single-trailer' trailer I've seen since The Shallows.  The WHOLE film is in this trailer.  They even gave away Zelda here.  Not sure how I feel about the changes from the source material.  It isn't even the same story anymore after this trailer.  This is what I gleaned from this trailer.  Pros (so far): - Wendigo plot element is here, though perhaps a little too much so.  We'll have to wait and see on that. - Casting (I guess.  I mean they'll never replace or outdo Fred Gwynne, but I can accept the prolific John Lithgow.) - Church looks gnarly.  Cons/Other: - Oh, everything else. - It doesn't necessarily look like Maine.  The characters now live in cabins in the woods it seems, going for a blatant, forced, easy creep factor instead of the alluring surprise of these events happening in a quiet New England neighborhood. - Changing the climactic demon child to Ellie is a bad idea, given the part she plays in the actual story/novel.  Should've been kept as Gage.  Now it's the girl from 'The Ring' LOL - Judging from all the changes, it also looks like there will be no sign or involvement of Rachel's parents beyond maybe the Zelda stuff, seen spoiled here in the trailer. - Apparently, the kids from 'Sinister' and 'Frank' from 'Donnie Darko' are here, so there's that. - There was never anything creepily ritualistic about the actual Pet Sematary that the children built, just the Wendigo-possessed Micmac Indian burial ground beyond. - The Micmac grounds seemingly being a swamp now (the shot was too quick to get a good detailed look, but it looked like a swamp) lends a little bit of a creep factor to it all, however, there was just something so deeply disturbing about the dry, frozen ground and wide-open rock formations of the original story.  At least there seems to be a coherent narrative here, and it still might be worth seeing.

There‚Äôs a scene of a woman in a rocking chair, you don‚Äôt know who she is yet either, but having read the book I have an inkling. I think they went into this knowing that so many people have already seen the original and read the book, and they wanted to knock your socks off by letting you know it‚Äôs gonna be Ellie instead of Gage. text: Have the studios not figured out that when you fuck with a Stephen King story and tell it inaccurately the adaptation almost 100% of the time will be a disappointment to fans of the source material, the original (mostly faithful) adaptation, AND anyone else that may see it. It's a lose lose situation when the things that are changed are the least interesting choices you could make. Look at the few King adaptations that are actually considered good movies AND were financially successful, they all stick pretty close to the original story. Shawshank went pretty much directly from the novella and even expanded a little and its widely considered one the greatest modern movies. Cheap jumpscares and stereotypical color grading will not make a good OR successful film, even if you have John Lithgow.

text: Imma rant here for a bit on why I disliked the trailer so much.   *SPOILER ALERT*       They changed the story! FFS, Ellie getting hit instead of Gage? Creepy kids who wears masks? Markings on trees as warnings? I am -this- close to putting it on the 'Only same title as the book' category along with Percy Jackson and I, Robot.   I get that it's a movie adaptation and changes will be made but c'mon, changing almost everything? Gage's death was the tipping point that pushed Louis' rationality. Sure he loved Ellie but it was obvious in the book (aka, source material) that Louis and Gage had a special bond. It would have been great if it was a hard cut of different scenes and end the trailer with a kite flying in the air with a little boy laughing. Remove those creepy kids who were rejected from the Purge movie, stay true to the very plot, and show a bit of bond between Judd and Louis. Damn!

text: Aaaaand I'm torn.  I've been excited about this project since I heard about it, and the cast looks solid.  I actually don't mind if a few liberties were taken with the source material (though it seems unlikely I'll ever see a film translation of the Hanratty story), but, for a film about resurrecting buried corpses - why does it look so clean?  Seriously, its like they took an industrial buffer to all aspects of the production design to remove as much burr as possible.  A BIG part of why I hold the '89 film in such high esteem is that it felt as grimy and real as raising kids in an old Northeast house can be.  I could relate more to that setting in all its drab accuracy then I ever could to a bunch of carefully lit tree glyphs that look to be lifted straight from Halloweentown.  I hope it proves me wrong,  I hope it doesn't fall into the trap of pleasing everyone to justify a huge budget, and I certainly hope its more than just jump scares with factory-fresh masks.

text: This looks really bad. Also the acting in the first movie looks waayy better considering these toddlers are obviously going to be all picture and no sound. Ellie dying really? They changed the whole dang story. The first movie with the baby being hit by the truck was so poignant. Especially because he used to play with a toy truck and make it crash into things. He loved trucks which is why he ran out onto the road. And they don't "try" to live with him dead, the Dad loses his mind and digs him up. The mother had no clue until she arrived home and he came at her all sweet but he killed her and it's like she wouldn't defend herself because he's her baby. Ellie was the one who foresaw that her dad was gonna dig up the brother. And the relationships between the characters were so good in the first movie. Gage was such a cheeky little boy, throwing food at his sister and shushing his mom. The dad had such a great relationship with Judd because he was the father figure he never had. In order for a horror movie to work cheap scares like this one is not the answer. Making us care about the characters and even relating to them is the answer. That "hug your daughter" was so flat I was face-palming. And don't get me started with the addition of the kids with masks. Lame lame lame.

text: In the book; when the Wendigo-possessed Gage confronts Judd, he tells him, "Hellow Jud, I've come to send your rotten stinking old soul straight to hell. You fucked with me once. text: So not only is Gage not the one who dies which means the killing is gonna be a thousand times less disturbing because it being a demonically possessed two year old was much more creepy, not only does this undermine Ellie's actual role from the book, not only do they seem to be altering the story's structure FOR NO REASON (Gage comes back and kills Judd and Rachel in one night and then Louis goes nuts afterwards) seemingly to pad out the length but the line 'she's not the only thing that came back' is such bullshit because it means that we now get a bunch of stupid creepy kids in masks. Because you know the corpse of your dead child reanimated and trying to kill you somehow isn't scary enough so let's throw in some out of nowhere kids in masks to flood the movie and basically act and cheap jump scare fodder.  Ergh, I kind of hope this is a fake trailer. Like its a deliberate misdirect and this is all fake footage to make Gage's death more 'shocking' as it stands they've replaced Gage Creed with a generic creepy girl, turned it from one terrifying night into a long drawn out haunted house and they've drawn the focus away from the horror of what can happen if you let grief overcome common sense for the sake of a bunch of jump scare 'creepy kids in masks' who have no personal attachment to Louis or Rachel so there's NO REASON TO CARE beyond cheap jumpscares.  Pet sematary was a dark, personal and very subtle story. If you didn't have the courage to deal with the heavy themes from that book you shouldn't have tried to adapt it. A few changes and updates are fine but you know what 'It' may have changed a few details from the book and 1990 miniseries but at least the basic plot remains the same. Jesus Christ I'm mad now, I went from hyped to this movie to really angry.

text: It's a remake, if you want to see the same exact story, go watch the original, or actually read the book. Having said that, the masks are really stupid and lame. That's my biggest complaint so far. I assumed they were in one flashback scene or something, and even that was too much. But it looks like they'll be all over this movie. And who was the idiot that decided to give too much away in the trailer? This damn thing needs a spoiler alert, because a good bit of it, is stuff that wasn't in the book or old movie. But I hope to see more of the wendigo, that was the creepiest part of the book, and it was left out of the old movie. Not sure about who they cast as Jud, would not have been my first choice. But he might suprise me. Overall it doesn't look like a bad remake, like say Rob Zombies Halloween. The original is still hands down the scariest movie I've ever seen. And the book is my all time favorite Stephen King novel. And on my top five books of all time. I'm definitely going to pay to see this. Hopefully they don't fuck up my childhood too much. Was raised on the first movie.

text: While this might look creepy, and while some parts do in general look better, first off, the daughter dose not get killed, she is the voice of reason that tries to pursued her father and mother with genuine love. Despite her warnings her father continues down his path of destruction and she tries to warn her mother after her father buries her brother not to go back and yet mom dose and is killed buy her own son.  this movie looks horrible, i urge all, please read the book, this movie just looks like a mess to me, as a devoted Stephen King fan, he has said himself, the true story is the book not the movie, so please read the book or listen to it unabridged on audio, but, as much as i love John as an actor, this just looks horrible to me. Seriously, cultish kids is so lame, in the book much scarier  as it progresses.  In essence, this book is sort of a twist retelling of frankenstein, in that the father whom is a doctor cannot give up his attachment or see that ends are natural and fine, and goes down an unnatural path, twist a human into a monster cause of his in ability to give up that which he loves.   While I know king could care less, as a constant reader, i'll be re-reading the book and skipping this over priced trash of an adaptation, i just don't know why hollywood has to take a good story that is all there, and the book needs no addition, and just doesn't adapted it wisely. I get it cannot go page by page, but when they start adding and removing as though they read the book and create a false untrue adaptation people aren't going to read then get false sense of the power of the story or the content of the story, please stop doing this hollywood.  But will say glad your doing the wendigo at least, but as for the daughter she doesn't die but if her father kills her mother and maybe possessed mother kills him at the end, in the book something i never thought of, but a friend said, so what do you think happens to the girl, if she comes back to the home...well i'll let you draw your own conclusions, but I think thats more scary cause yah the one innocent child your left going oh, now whats her fate. Also, i don't remember there being markers in the book, i think what to me was more scary was in the book that the presence that wants a human to possess works, lures, Judd against his own better insight, and in the end he realizes it before its two late cause at one point he sampled the forbidden by bring back his dog.   Personally, my favorite book by King is IT, but his scariest to me is Pet Sematary, again please please please, don't spend your hard earned money on this, read or listen to the book, use your imagination and enjoy the true story as it should be.  Have a wonderful day and make some magic for yourself cause life is to short to be ordinary.

text: as someone whos read the book and loved the first movie, this thing is going to be terrible. theyve shown in their trailer that they have removed everything that made the original film truly frightening and replaced it with a bunch of cliches. Zelda, in the film, was played my a man, in order to give it a physically warped and psychologically disturbing feel. and it worked. it worked so well, they used the same tactic in the film, The Ring, with Samara, with similar results. But now, theyre acting like thats an amateur approach. So, they just cast a little girl and its not going to feel like anything else but a little girl. its going to be sad, not bone chilling... They opted for some pretty cat, made to look menacing with cgi, insted of using a real cat that looks and sounds menacing on its own. They wanted a pretty cat. this already tells me they are relying on looks and cgi to carry the film, and ignoring what makes the book and film truly scary, the realism and depth... Using Ellie as the child Louis loses, insted of Gage, well, come on, how gut wrenching was it to see a toddler die by running out into the road, chasing a kite? theres no way using Ellie is going to lend more to the emotional power of the story. That moment in the original film haunted people for a lifetime. They wanted to use Ellie, so they could give the dead child more depth and more to do, well, thats just lazy filmaking. because you dont need to add more PLOT to a BOOK with plot to spare. And it was the subtlety that made Gage so scary. He was not that mobile, but his parents grief caused them to welcome the little zombie into their arms without fear of consequences. thats the point of the book. thats the point of the whole story. how disarmed a grieving parent becomes to logic and danger, in the midst of their bereavement. i cringe at the thought of what they want to make of Ellies character. i just know its going to be garbage... People keep mentioning "the wendigo", like we are going to get to see the wendigo, well, the wendigo is not a central theme of the book. the book does not make the wendigo a character, it is a passing reference to mythology. and barely focused on to any substantial degree with concern for the plot. im like, this story does not NEED a MONSTER to make it scary or carry out its design. it is scary enough as it is. and how could they even have enough film time to add more story or plot elements? the problem with adapting books to film is you have too much story and not enough screen time. so what are they thinking? seriously?.... and the fact that they are just opting not to let Judd have a new england accent, that is what painted the eerie tone of Judds character in the book and movie. It was creepy. the accent gets into your psyche and lends to the ambiance of the story. paints a mood. theres no reason not to have it, unless John Lithgow just cant do a new england accent for some reason. but its an easy accent, and whats the problem...... also, what is the deal with the kids wearing animal masks? thats nowhere in the book. are they trying to combine children of the corn for flair, or tongue in cheek, since its stephen king? UNNECESSARY. again, this story is scary enough without all this garbage. and i doubt theyll have time to flesh out relationships between main characters with all this "reboot" filler garbage. theres no cult of children in the book, or first film. and it wouldnt make sense if there was. its not part of the story. so how are they going to add that without it being pointless?... and pascow and timmy were two very crucial elements in the story and first film, that were already done to perfection. changing pascows character(im not talking about his race, but his origin. making him something more powerful and wise.) and omitting the story of timmy is totally needless. pascow is already everything the story needs him to be. why would you add extra layers when the story doesnt require it?...... Also, why show the scene where Judd gets his achilles tendon cut IN THE TRAILER??? are you trying to give the entire movie away? That scene in the first film was a huge punch to the psyche, and youre just going to waste that moment for a gag in the preview or some kind of throwback nod? break the fourth wall some more why dont you. do you even care about making a film thats going to be scary, or is this a joke? because it looks like a joke. it looks like that is the whole point of this effort, to make fun of the original film and book asif they are basic. man, you cant hold a candle to the original. you dont understand HALF of what is necessary to do what the originals did and  i feel embarrassed for you....... maybe you should take your own advice, "sometimes dead is better." i have a feeling thats going to ring poetic after this thing opens.

text: I gotta say that making it clear that Ellie is swapped for Gage in the trailer was a shit move (not the fact that it happens, but the fact that it's shown in the trailer), even if you don't know the source material it's still a shit move. It would have been far better for the old readers and fans (and even the new audience) to have been hit with that detail in the theater, now any impact that the twist might have had is completely gone. While I'm feeling pretty meh about knowing in advance that Ellie will be getting a close-up with the Orinco truck instead of Gage, maybe it will still be able to bring something fresh so I'll give it a shot. I'm really wishing that they don't give us any front and center interactions with the Wendigo because there are already too many "creature features" these days and they all lack subtlety. I hope that any wendigo appearances are kept fleeting and at a distance, and that we don't get a whole herd of revenants by the end of the film. So far I get the feeling we won't be seeing much of the Goldmans as Rachel seems to be at home for the heavy bits, if so, then we'll lose some of the excellent dynamic between Louis and Irwin. The source content is great, the movie itself may still turn out good, but this trailer fucking sucks due to the heavy exposition, this is a terribly executed trailer imho. TL;DR Shitty trailer, possibly good movie.

text: Things like this usually don‚Äôt scare me. Im a fairly fearless person, but I am also an animal lover. This reminded me of a dream I had a few years ago. I hadn‚Äôt even heard of pet semetary. In this dream, I would walk out of my high school on a slightly snowy day. Not a person or car in sight. In the parking lot would be one of my beloved, deceased dogs. I would walk over to them, cry and hug them, glad to see them for only a moment more, as I had wished since the day they passed. They would gladly take the affection, then pause, and walk over to the road. I would follow. They would stop in the middle of the roadway and sit. No matter what I thought about the danger, I would kneel down and pet them. The dog would smile at me menacingly. Somewhat similar to Smile.jpg, the somewhat creepy image of a husky or something with a human like smile. After it smiled, it would look down the road, and there would be a semi heading straight toward us at full speed. I would die along with the dog. This happened quite a few times. The dream restarting over and over. Each time with a different pet. This trailer scared me, and I can‚Äôt wait for the movie.

text: 8th grade, I'll never forget it. Summer of 1999. My friend was having a sleep over one summer night, but earlier that day I was left home by my parents while they ran errands. I did what I always did and watched TV to kill time. This strange movie had just came on, so I decided to watch because I loved a good horror flick. So, I'm watching in my house ALONE and about 15-20 minutes in, I turned off the tv and just stared at it. I was like...NOPE. (Read more)   Then, what do you know.  It was the same movie my sleepover friends decided to watch that very night. So, not wanting to feel like a chicken in front of them, guess who decided to stay. I was so messed up after the original movie for sooo long. My parents was like "what the hell did you watch over there?"

text: I used to live in a very secluded area of the north Georgia mountains and we use to have Pet Cemetery as our town mascot so to speak  The things that happened there, happened before that book was even written.  I used to hike long distances right out the back door for hours through those hills just exploring and one day I stumbled upon a relatively large pet cemetery. It was laid out the exact same way in circles. Well, there was a few cats that wandered around the woods and you could hear them hissing and screaming at night. This one scraggly, beat up tom cat stayed around there for years. He wouldnt let you near him and would always walk off when you came outside. He wouldn't run, he would just slowly walk away and periodically turn and look.  One day, this cat was just laying on my porch dead. I felt bad for the old guy and carried him over 3 mountains to that cemetery I had found. This is no shit people. I had this dead, solid stiff cat in a black bag right behind me as I dug a hole at the outer edge of the cemetery.  I heard the bag behind me suddenly violently shaking. I turn around and just the bag is laying there and the cat is gone  You can smell this very strong dead odor. I don't see the cat, hear the cat, nothing. About 3 months later I'm out fixing a hole on the chicken coup and something catches my eye  Its that fucking cat up I  the woods between two bushes.  He just stares at me and you can tell hes sorta wet and scraggly. He turns around and slowly walks away and I never saw him again.

text: It was utter shit. Worse than the original. The drudging music drowned out any subtlety or ambience, and the only time it ever went away was in anticipation of incredibly predictable jumpscares. It also wussed out on the violence and language that the book had, with so many pointless and ineffective gimmicks that it came off as a blundering first attempt at a horror movie made by people with no appreciation for the source material. The moments of exposition were particularly heavy handed.  It's as if the directors are pussies without any imagination at all, piggybacking off King's name. Plus, the special effects mostly consisted of make up, green screen, and a truck. Where the fuck did the budget go, honestly? Save yourself the money, don't see this pile of trash.

text: I was really enjoying this movie until the end. After the daughter was resurrected the movie crumbled. Having the little girl getting killed instead of Gage was an interesting shift from the novel, but having her converse with her father and mother after she rose from the dead 100% castrated the horror element. It did the worst thing possible you can do in a horror movie; it personified the evil hence nullifying the mystery of it, effectively robbing it of all its potency. After that point it became at best a generic slasher flick, at worst a comedy.  "Hey kiddo, it looks like you have some staples in the back of your head here. Don't let the kids at school tease you about them, they're only there to hold your brains in your skull, they're just immature, sweetheart. See you at the bus stop after school."  I mean, come the fuck on. It's too bad really as the movie was doing really well up until the end, but the original movie is superior because for all its cheese and corniness, at least it kept the barrier between the mysterious evil of the dead and the malevolence that gave rise to it contrasted against the naive but hopeless hopes of the living in taking desperate measures to recover what was forever and irrecoverably lost. Here it doesn't, and the film fails because of it.

text: I just got out of seeing the movie and personally I didn't think it was that bad. Since it was basically shown in the trailer I don't think this is much of a spoiler, but I don't think that switching Gage's death was Ellie's detracted from the story at all. Unless you're a rigid nostalgia junkie who only wants to see a verbatim recreation of the original adaptation I don't think you'll see that much of a difference between them switching Ellie and Gage's roles in the film. I give props to the filmmakers for trying something original. They know that the original Pet Sematary is a classic horror film of the 80's and that the audience of the 2019 film are going to be familiar with the original so they decided to give you something new that doesn't stray too far from the spirit of the original film. My only gripes with the film would be that they glossed over some things that I believe deserved more attention and the jump scares didn't really do much for me.

text: *TO THOSE THAT READ THE BOOK AND ARE ANTICIPATING THE ATMOSPHERIC COSMIC TERROR THEREIN:* You may be slightly disappointed.   I must stress that the movie has a pacing problem, introducing events at an accelerated rate that disallows the relation we had to the characters from the older film and especially the book. Additional thereto, the Lovecraftian Cosmic Horror is largely absent with greater emphasis being placed on body horror, gore grotesquerie, and jump scares. There is, to an extent, still a degree of psychological suspense; the soundtrack is wonderful; and the characters are well acted but, otherwise, this film seems to be more an overbudgeted cash grab seizing upon the renewed interest in King adaptations. To those ignorant of or unfamiliar to King literature, the book in question in particular, then it is a decent horror movie that is worth the money but, if you were a true diehard fan of both the book and the first movie, then this sucker will come up short.   I loved seeing it, I will probably go to see it again but, it is by no means the most faithful cinematization of the original story. It does throw in some original twists and turns though so, at least they tried to make it surprising to viewers like yours truly but, it was not as good as "IT" in my opinion, nor the 1980's film.

The trailer didn't need to show anything further than the cat coming back, and even that is revealing too much.

text: Okay, so i watched this movie over spring break. Now, i'm a big fan of the original, fred Gwynne was amazing. The original creeped me out as a kid. This movie however, had me scared shitless the entire break. The ost was amazing, clarke played louis better than midkiff, and of course, lithgow playing jud was fantastic. Now SPOILER ALERT, for those who didnt like the change from gage to ellie dying i understand. For those who said they didnt have the balls to kill gage, you should've watched the movie before judging it seeing as they all die. Ellie was 5x creepier than gage, and he was scary. Each person has something that makes their skin crawl. For me, its contortions, possessions, and reanimation. These all combined in this movie for a horrifying yet great movie that left my heart pounding all the way to its bitter ending.  WARNING MORE SPOILERS  You can argue that both movies have similar endings, but they seem to overlook the fact that in the original louis was able to kill gage/ the reanimated. In the new one, no one, not even the other sibling escaped death.  All in all, this movie left me scared for a week and them some. Now keep in mind that these are just my thoughts, and i dont want to force anyone to agree with me (though that may be a bit hypocritical after all i just said) it may not satisfy everyone, but it left me content. Have a good night everyone.üòÅüòÅüòÅ

text: I think this, honestly, was a marketing plunder. I understand that the 2019 version is adapted to suit a new audience who possibly hasn't seen the original 1980's version of the movie, much less read the book, because both were from a time before they were born, but it seems so clumsily employed! As a child of the 90's, I was extremely excited to hear this movie was being re-made. Literally, I got scared just thinking about it, with the memories rushing back (LOL)... until I saw the trailer. Getting back to my original point, I don't think they set out to ruin the original book's story, or to spoil the ending of THIS story with that ridiculous trailer, but succeeded with both. If they had done their homework, they could have figured out what the 'target audience' wanted, which would have been the original fans of King's work, the generation x and early millennials who can still remember the books and original campy 80's version. We would have been the ones who would have really wanted to see it for the nostalgia and to compare it to a closer version of what we remember and expect. I think, perhaps, it was a lost opportunity, and could have been a much bigger box office smash, if only they had asked their audience, or had a small research project on what this segment felt about changing the killer *spoiler* to ellie, and whatever else they are complaining about. I can understand that today's audiences have been very sheltered from the way the world was when we were younger. Maybe that's a good thing.  The angry comments about this movie seem awkwardly silly, and it shows we could all soften up a bit more, and be more open-minded. It's not the 80's or 90's anymore. This is the preferred way that horror movies are consumed now. I could go see the movie, and waste $20-30, or even read the original book if wanted to relive my childhood - but that phase is over. I am 34 years old, and I don't have the time to waste on it any longer, only to write this very detailed commenton youtube, like a nerd. ;)

text: I finished the book 3 days ago and watched the movie today so here are some differences I noticed:  Introduction of the Pet Sematary - in the book the whole family and Jud walk up there, in the movie Ellie sees kids go there to bury a dog then wanders up there herself. This is also where we meet Jud for the first time in the movie.  Norma is alive in the book then dies. In the movie she‚Äôs already dead. Which I was okay with because her character wasn‚Äôt a crucial part in the book. She was pretty old and ill. In the book Rachel and Ellie have no idea that Church died since they were away for Thanksgiving. This gives Louis a chance to bury him and come back which is the cat they see when they get back.  The death of Zelda - she did not fall down a dumbwaiter but she was as ill as they showed her in the movie.  It was Gage who died in the street - not Ellie.  Rachel and the other child do go to her parents house, but only Rachel comes back when she thinks something is wrong with Louis.¬†  Rachel dies in Jud‚Äôs house by Gage, not in their own house.  Louis does not see Rachel between the time she leaves to her parents, to the time he finds her in Jud‚Äôs house dead. There was no scuffle at their house.  Louis sets Jud‚Äôs house on fire and carries Rachel to the Pet Sematary.

text: Sematary or cemetery? Was confused ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è by the spelling, so I checked for WHYYYY KING DID THIS, HE STRATEGICALLY DID THIS. OF COURSE HE DID! üòÇ üôÑ King's spelling of cemetery as sematary is intentional‚Äîit is a use of realism, which is the practice in writing to accurately represent real life. In this case, we have a young child who has phonetically spelled cemetery, a word for a place set apart for the burial or entombment of the dead, on a sign without a dictionary on hand. In Middle English, the word was spelled cimitery. It is from Anglo-French cimiterie, which, in turn, is from Late Latin cimiterium and coemeterium, and ultimately from Greek koimƒìtƒìrion, meaning "sleeping chamber," and the verb koiman, "to put to sleep." (Considering this orthographic evolution from Greek to Latin to Anglo-French, we can certainly understand the child's misspelling‚Äîat least he or she applied phonetics to spell it out.) ‚Äúthanks Dictionary, for clearing that one up‚Äù

text: I just watched the movie, it's  not bad but not good either,  just meh despite the good performances by the actors who had to work with a mediocre script. A lot of missed opportunities here, since the story in the novel is very original and they could have done something way darker and terrifying. It's like producers and director are afraid of making a proper horror film, as though if it's too scary people won't want to see it, so they water it down and turn it into an undercover family movie. That's why so many people are of the opinion that to this day the greatest horror movie ever made is The Exorcist: every one involved took the story dead seriously and pulled no punches in making the film, and people heard it was scary as fuck and still waited in line to see it at the theatre. And regarding how it compares withe 1989 version, well the '89 version is better, more intense and raw.  Give this story to Robert Eggers (The Witch, The Lighthouse) or Ari Aster (Hereditary, Midsommar) and then you'll see a horror movie.

text: A few things to note if you're interested in this movie: The trailer makes it seem like something else entirely. There are no monsters or scary children with masks in the movie. Spoiler: at the beginning, you'll see children with masks. But they're not the scary crazy tribal children with masks the trailer portrays them to be. I don't think this in general is a spoiler, because you figure it out pretty quickly in the movie.    It strays a LOT from the novel. It strays a LOT from the first adaptation of the book. It's different, and personally, i think it's better and "makes more sense" (or as much sense any horror movie could make). So yes, this version is based on the novel, but don't expect it to be a line-by-line exact adaptation. I love Stephen King, but I also love this different version.    That being said, it's definitely not the best horror movie I've watched. It's not even in my top 10. But I do recommend you watch it if you like SK or like horror in general. It won't be a waste of your time.
